      <div xml:id="NA101-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piṉṉiṉṟa talaivaṉ (EN, ER, ET, EV: talaimakaṉ) tōḻi kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE who was standing behind said when the confidante was listening.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA101">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            muṟṟā mañcaṭ pacumpuṟaṅ kaṭuppac</l>
<l>            cuṟṟiya piṇara cūḻkaḻi yiṟaviṉ</l>
<l>            kaṇaṅkoḷ kuppai yuṇaṅkutiṟa ṉōkkip</l>
<l>            puṉṉaiyaṅ koḻuniḻaṉ muṉṉuyttup parappun</l>
<l>            tuṟainaṇi yirunta pākkamu muṟainaṉi </l>
<l>            yiṉituma ṉaḷitō tāṉē tuṉitīrn</l>
<l>            takaṉṟa valku laitamai nucuppiṉ</l>
<l>            mīṉeṟi paratavar maṭamakaṇ</l>
<l>            māṉēr nōkkaṅ kāṇā vūṅkē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Very pleasing indeed it [was] – pitiful it [is now]</l>
<l rend="indent">to stay in the village too that was near the ghat,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where they(?)<note place="foot">If we have a single subject for the sub-construction (<term xml:lang="ta">nōkki</term> - <term xml:lang="ta">uyttu</term> - <term xml:lang="ta">parappum</term>), it is elliptical. The oblique form <term xml:lang="ta">iṟaviṉ</term> suggests at least that <term xml:lang="ta">parappum</term> has to be understood as a transitive verb.</note> look at the drying opulence of grouped heaps</l>
<l rend="indent2">of prawn from the surrounding backwaters, in coiled roughness<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">iṟavu</term> is, according to T.V.G., a kind of fish, but the description here might rather point to a kind of prawn or shrimps - if <term xml:lang="ta">cuṟṟiya</term> means something like “coiled up”, but what else can it mean?</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">similar to the green back of unripe Tumeric,</l>
<l rend="indent">bring them in front of the rich Puṉṉai shade [and] spread [them],</l>
<l rend="indent">– before seeing the deer-like look</l>
<l rend="indent">of the innocent daughter of the fish-catching fishermen,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with a waist fitting beautifully to [her] broad hips,</l>
<l rend="indent2">ending disgust.<note place="foot">Is <term xml:lang="ta">tuṉi tīrntu</term> just one of the numerous conventional attributes meaning "faultless" or does it convey something more significant, as the fact that seeing the girl has given HIM a new desire for life (cf. <term xml:lang="ta">tuṉi</term> in KT 290.4)?</note></l>
        </lg>
